g, etc. The Process Support and Compliance Section is also responsible for the regulatory compliance functions related to Biosolids, including the EPA 503 regulations and multi-state regulations associated with biosolids management practices including land application, composting and landfilling. The Section Chief is responsible for the management of several multi-million dollar chemical contracts, including sodium hypochlorite, caustic soda, ferric chloride and sodium bisulfite. The Section Chief will also be responsible for the continued deployment of the HACH WIMS information system and the development of a multi-media calendar and enhanced document management system, as well as the implementation of the Process Engineering training framework.\n\nJob Tasks/Duties:\nThe Section Chief of Process Support and Compliance has a broad mandate that includes:\nServe as Administrative Engineer for maintaining compliance with all SPDES permit deliverables for New York City\u2019s 14 wastewater treatment plants.\nProvide technical and administrative direction to the Process Support and Compliance Section staff to ensure that consistent and proper methods are used in calculations and reporting, and that the process requirements of the SPDES permits and all applicable Consent Orders are complied with.\nMaintain weekly, monthly and annual metrics on plant performance, non-compliance events, critical equipment and energy consumption for the Commissioner and staff for evaluating and complying with SPDES permits.\nProduce living documents and reports that track critical equipment status and maintain updates and provide compilation summary for upper management and/or notifications to NYSDEC.\nPerform assessment of wet weather performance of all 14 NYC wastewater treatment plants in order to determine compliance with the CSO best management practice of maximizing flow to all of NYC\u2019s wastewater treatment plants.\nRepresents the Bureau of Wastewater Treatment at technical meetings, with regulatory authorities, the public, consultants and other City agencies.\nMake recommendations to Senior Management in the use of resources, material and personnel, in order to optimize efficiency and meet SPDES permit and Consent Order requirements.\nWith the implementation support of the Bureau\u2019s information technology (IT) team, will develop an multi-media calendar and enhanced document management system (MMCDM) by conducting a top-down review of compliance/permitting activities for water, biosolids and air compliance/permitting, defining the operational requirements of the MMCDM, supporting IT in the creation of the software application including preparation of training materials and deploying the application within the Division of Operations Support.\nWill be responsible for the implementation of the Process Engineering training framework, to develop the technical abilities of entry level chemical and environmental engineers, including wastewater resource recovery fundamentals, compliance/permitting requirements, SCADA & PLC programming, research project execution and process optimization.\n\nMinimum Qual Requirements\n\n1. A valid New York State License as a Professional Engineer.\n\n2. Six (6) years of full-time satisfactory experience in chemical engineering, civil engineering, electrical engineering, environmental engineering, mechanical engineering, or plan examining work, at least two (2) years of which must have been in an executive, managerial, or administrative capacity.\n\nPreferred Skills\n\nProfessional Engineering registration in NYS, or ability to obtain it within 6 months of hire.\n\n1. Familiarity with sewage treatment and collection facilities, equipment and processes related to wastewater treatment.\n2. Experience with regulatory reporting and negotiations with City, State and Federal regulatory bodies.\n3. Ability to: represent the work unit to supervisors and other groups; coordinate with other work units and organizations; pla